{"action": "edit", "code": "def find_red_and_teal_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n    red_pixels = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    teal_pixels = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    return (red_pixels, teal_pixels)\ndef main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    r, t = find_red_and_teal_pixels(input_grid)\n    r_c, t_c = check_pixels(r, t)\n    out = color_teal_pixels(r, t, r_c, t_c, input_grid)\n    return out\ndef color_teal_pixels(r: Tuple[np.ndarray], t: Tuple[np.ndarray], r_c: int, t_c: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    According to condition of pixels in teal, starting from existed teal pixels, color pixels in teal in the same column \n    if the condition is 1 else in the same row, until the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, choose the \n    column away from red pixels if the condition is 1 else the row away from red pixels, continue coloring until next \n    time the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, loop above steps. You need use r and t to judge the next \n    pixel should be left or right, for example if origin teal pixels are in the right edge line, you should color pixels \n    in teal left.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    r (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of red pixels in the input grid.\n    t (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of teal pixels in the input grid.\n    r_c (int): Condition of pixels in red.\n    t_c (int): Condition of pixels in teal.\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): Input grid containing the pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    np.ndarray: The updated grid after coloring the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    out = input_grid.copy()\n    if t_c == 1:\n        for i in range(len(t[0])):\n            row = t[0][i]\n            col = t[1][i]\n            if r_c == 1:\n                if col < r[1][0]:\n                    out[row, col] = pink\n                else:\n                    out[row, col] = blue\n            else:\n                for j in range(col, input_grid.shape[1]):\n                    if input_grid[row, j] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[row, j] = blue\n                for j in range(col, -1, -1):\n                    if input_grid[row, j] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[row, j] = pink\n    else:\n        for i in range(len(t[0])):\n            row = t[0][i]\n            col = t[1][i]\n            if r_c == 2:\n                if row < r[0][0]:\n                    out[row, col] = pink\n                else:\n                    out[row, col] = blue\n            else:\n                for j in range(row, input_grid.shape[0]):\n                    if input_grid[j, col] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[j, col] = blue\n                for j in range(row, -1, -1):\n                    if input_grid[j, col] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[j, col] = pink\n    return out\ndef check_pixels(r: Tuple[np.ndarray], t: Tuple[np.ndarray]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Judge the condition of r and t respectively, if all pixel in it are in the same row return 1, \n    if in the same column return 2.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    r (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of red pixels in the input grid.\n    t (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of teal pixels in the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    Tuple[int, int]: A tuple containing the condition of pixels in red and teal respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    r_c = 1 if len(set(r[0])) == 1 else 2\n    t_c = 1 if len(set(t[0])) == 1 else 2\n    return (r_c, t_c)", "user_code": "def main(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    r, t = `find the red pixels and teal pixels in the grid`(input_grid)\n    r_c, t_c = `judge the condition of r and t, if all pixel in it are in the same row return 1, if in the same column return 2`(r, t)\n    out = `Then according to condition of pixels in teal, starting from existed teal pixels, color pixels in teal in the same column if the condition is 1 else in the same row, until the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, choose the column away from red pixels if the condition is 1 else the row away from red pixels, continue coloring until next time the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, loop above steps.`(r, t, r_c, t_c, input_grid)\n    return out", "gpt_code": "def find_red_and_teal_pixels(input_grid: np.ndarray) -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]:\n    red_pixels = np.where(input_grid == red)\n    teal_pixels = np.where(input_grid == teal)\n    return (red_pixels, teal_pixels)\ndef color_teal_pixels(r: Tuple[np.ndarray], t: Tuple[np.ndarray], r_c: int, t_c: int, input_grid: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    \"\"\"\n    According to condition of pixels in teal, starting from existed teal pixels, color pixels in teal in the same column \n    if the condition is 1 else in the same row, until the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, choose the \n    column away from red pixels if the condition is 1 else the row away from red pixels, continue coloring until next \n    time the pixel has same row or column with any red pixel, loop above steps. You need use r and t to judge the next \n    pixel should be left or right, for example if origin teal pixels are in the right edge line, you should color pixels \n    in teal left.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    r (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of red pixels in the input grid.\n    t (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of teal pixels in the input grid.\n    r_c (int): Condition of pixels in red.\n    t_c (int): Condition of pixels in teal.\n    input_grid (np.ndarray): Input grid containing the pixels.\n    \n    Returns:\n    np.ndarray: The updated grid after coloring the teal pixels.\n    \"\"\"\n    out = input_grid.copy()\n    if t_c == 1:\n        for i in range(len(t[0])):\n            row = t[0][i]\n            col = t[1][i]\n            if r_c == 1:\n                if col < r[1][0]:\n                    out[row, col] = pink\n                else:\n                    out[row, col] = blue\n            else:\n                for j in range(col, input_grid.shape[1]):\n                    if input_grid[row, j] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[row, j] = blue\n                for j in range(col, -1, -1):\n                    if input_grid[row, j] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[row, j] = pink\n    else:\n        for i in range(len(t[0])):\n            row = t[0][i]\n            col = t[1][i]\n            if r_c == 2:\n                if row < r[0][0]:\n                    out[row, col] = pink\n                else:\n                    out[row, col] = blue\n            else:\n                for j in range(row, input_grid.shape[0]):\n                    if input_grid[j, col] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[j, col] = blue\n                for j in range(row, -1, -1):\n                    if input_grid[j, col] == red:\n                        break\n                    out[j, col] = pink\n    return out\ndef check_pixels(r: Tuple[np.ndarray], t: Tuple[np.ndarray]) -> Tuple[int, int]:\n    \"\"\"\n    Judge the condition of r and t respectively, if all pixel in it are in the same row return 1, \n    if in the same column return 2.\n    \n    Parameters:\n    r (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of red pixels in the input grid.\n    t (Tuple[np.ndarray]): Tuple containing the row indices of teal pixels in the input grid.\n    \n    Returns:\n    Tuple[int, int]: A tuple containing the condition of pixels in red and teal respectively.\n    \"\"\"\n    r_c = 1 if len(set(r[0])) == 1 else 2\n    t_c = 1 if len(set(t[0])) == 1 else 2\n    return (r_c, t_c)", "holes": {"find_red_and_teal_pixels": "find the red pixels and teal pixels in the grid", "